  '564c8c2b-b6f1-4ccc-b4fa-66810ff52032',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Celery Idempotency — Designing Tasks to Survive Duplicate Execution$escape$,
  $escape$Celery's at-least-once delivery guarantee means your tasks will occasionally run more than once — on worker crashes, broker restarts, or visibility timeout expiry with acknowledgment mode `acks_late=True`. Without idempotency, duplicates corrupt state.

The core pattern: make your task's side effects conditional on state you persist externally. Use Redis or your database as a deduplication store keyed on `self.request.id` (the task UUID). Before doing any work, check if that ID has already been processed; if so, return early.

For database-backed tasks, a unique constraint on a `task_id` column is often cleaner than a separate Redis key — the INSERT itself becomes the idempotency check via `ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING`.

Set `acks_late=True` with `reject_on_worker_lost=True` so tasks are re-queued on hard crashes, but always pair this with idempotent logic — not instead of it. For tasks with external side effects (emails, webhooks), store a `sent_at` timestamp and skip if already set. Celery's `task_always_eager` in tests makes it easy to validate re-execution behavior without a real broker.$escape$,
  $escape$import redis
from celery import shared_task

r = redis.Redis()

@shared_task(bind=True, acks_late=True, reject_on_worker_lost=True)
def send_welcome_email(self, user_id: int):
    dedup_key = f"task:done:{self.request.id}"
    if r.get(dedup_key):
        return {"status": "skipped", "reason": "duplicate"}

    # perform side effect
    _dispatch_email(user_id)

    # mark complete with TTL matching your visibility window
    r.set(dedup_key, 1, ex=86400)
    return {"status": "sent"}$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
