INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'a8defd3a-621e-49ca-b326-adecb769e995',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Celery + Redis Broker — Lists vs Streams vs Pub/Sub and What Actually Persists$escape$,
  $escape$Celery's Redis broker uses Lists by default — tasks are pushed with LPUSH and consumed via BRPOP. This is fast and battle-tested, but comes with a critical gotcha: if a worker dies mid-execution, the task disappears unless you tune `visibility_timeout` in `BROKER_TRANSPORT_OPTIONS`. Celery re-queues tasks only if the timeout expires before an ACK, so set it longer than your longest task.

Redis Pub/Sub is a hard no for Celery task queues — it's fire-and-forget with zero persistence. Any message published while a worker is down is gone permanently. Celery has no pub/sub broker transport for good reason.

Redis Streams (XADD/XREADGROUP) aren't natively supported as a Celery broker transport, but the List-based transport approximates stream semantics via `BRPOP` blocking reads. For true durability, the real lever is Redis persistence config: AOF with `appendfsync everysec` gives you near-zero data loss on crash; RDB snapshots alone can lose minutes of tasks. Pair AOF with `CELERY_TASK_ACKS_LATE = True` to ensure tasks aren't ACK'd until the worker finishes, not just when received.$escape$,
  $escape$# celery_config.py
app.config_from_object({
    'broker_url': 'redis://localhost:6379/0',
    'result_backend': 'redis://localhost:6379/1',

    # Re-queue task if worker dies before this window expires
    # Must be > your longest-running task duration
    'broker_transport_options': {
        'visibility_timeout': 7200,  # 2 hours
    },

    # ACK only after task completes — safer with AOF persistence
    'task_acks_late': True,
    'task_reject_on_worker_lost': True,
})$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
